Notes: The only other thing to do this weekend is to begin thinking about unit 3. There will be a full unit description posted on Monday, but for the moment... remember how I told you to always think about purpose, audience, and form when writing? Well, for this unit, you get to decide on all of them - what you're writing about and your aims for the piece (purpose), who you're writing to and how this will alter the tone/layout/language/etc (audience), and the best delivery system for the information (form). The only rule is that it needs to be a researched piece (and uses that effective research to create a greater effect in terms of argument). This means it could be anything from a piece of political poetry (that uses footnotes to explain how research--of other poetry, critical texts on creative writing, and background research--has shaped the piece), a journalistic piece about some facet of the university (maybe one that could even be sent for publication in the Collegian, if that interests you), a tongue-in-cheek/serious/whatever guide to <insert audience> on <insert topic>, an academic essay on <insert whatever topic interests you here>, a vlog about a particular issue to a particular audience, or just about anything else. Seriously, as with unit 1, the sky is the limit here; it just needs to be effectively researched, and written with your chosen purpose/audience/form in mind!

Notes:
Think up a list of concepts and ideas that you are not used to questioning (our attitude to authority/parents, a particular life goal, what you think about a particular group/political party/etc, a religious or social belief), and first of all figure out what (or who) has influenced your thinking in regards to these concepts/ideas. For example, attitudes to authority might be impacted by...
... our parents
... our culture
... our biology
... our education
... our class
... our race
... etc

Name: brainstorm positions of authority
Notes: Think about (and jot down some notes) regarding how these various elements have shaped your own attitudes. For example, in regards to attitudes to authority being shaped by your parents... maybe they were very liberal, and always wanted you to query things, or maybe you came from a household where kids should be seen but not heard. Did you fit neatly into the mold your parents had constructed for your personality, or did you rebel? What events or stories from your life are archetypal of the sort of attitudes towards authority that your parents attempted to inculcate (both things they did in influencing you, and the ways in which this has played out in your own life)? For culture (again in regards to attitudes towards authority), maybe think about popular movies or TV series (or more interestingly, common trends in these forms of entertainment), or about the history of your particular country... etc, etc. Try to think critically about all these things, as if you were examining another person with these views/ideas. Where do they seem to make sense? Which ones are merely held because they have been unquestioningly transmitted? Which ones clearly need more thought/research? Do this exercise for a few of those concepts and ideas that you thought up in section 1.
